2026-04-16 12:38:39 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['sensor-operated relay in control (ambient sensor) module'] hypothesis_explanation='Battery and power‑supply LED show the 12 V source is healthy, and 11.99 V is confirmed on the control module input pair. However, at the control module output pair we only see ~0.36 V vs ~0 V under operating conditions, and this does not change with ambient light or with large adjustments of the timing and sensitivity potentiometers. That means the control module never delivers the 12 V through to its output, so the load module cannot energize the lamp, explaining that it is now off and that earlier it was periodically flickering as the failing part intermittently made contact.\n\nGiven the circuit description, the only element that actually connects/disconnects the 12 V path from input to output is the sensor‑operated relay (its contacts and/or coil/driver). A fault in the relay (stuck open contacts, burned contact, open‑circuit coil, or failed driver so the coil never pulls in) is fully consistent with:\n- Correct input supply to the control module\n- Very low, non‑switching voltage at its output\n- No dependence on light level or potentiometer settings\n- Initial intermittent behavior followed by complete failure.\n\nTherefore the most probable root cause is a faulty relay assembly in the control (ambient sensor) module. Replacing/repairing this component should restore proper operation, with 12 V being switched to the load when ambient light is below the threshold.'
