Someone executed a (additional) diagnostic action on the system. The action (type, target_component, description, outcome) was: 
TYPE: Test,
TARGET: light sensor / comparator stage in control (ambient sensor) module,
DESCRIPTION: With power on, measure the DC voltage at the control module node that drives the relay coil (comparator output) relative to the control module ground, under both bright light and darkness over the sensor. Also measure the voltage across the light sensor element itself. Determine whether the comparator output ever reaches a valid high (near battery +) or low (near 0 V) level, and whether it responds to changes in ambient light.,
RESULT: The control relay drive node sits at about 12 V on the (+) side and 0.36 V on the (−) side in both bright and dark conditions, indicating no observable change in comparator output with light level. The ambient light sensor shows about 0.12 V on the (+) side and near 0 V on the (−) side, also with no change between bright and dark measurements.
Current persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:
No circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.


2026-04-16 12:39:05 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient light sensor in control (ambient sensor) module', 'comparator / control IC in control (ambient sensor) module', 'associated bias / feedback network around comparator in control (ambient sensor) module'] hypothesis_explanation='Power is good into the control module (≈12 V at its input) but essentially no useful output appears at the control output cables (≈0.36 V and ≈0 V). The relay contacts and coil have been ruled out by a prior repair attempt.\n\nDirect probing of the light‑sensor/comparator stage shows:\n- The node that should *switch* to drive the relay coil instead sits with ≈12 V on the supply side and ≈0.36 V on the low side, independent of light level.\n- The light‑sensor element itself sits at ≈0.12 V and ≈0 V, also fixed, independent of light.\n\nIn a healthy circuit the sensor voltage and comparator output should both vary significantly between near‑0 V and near‑supply as the ambient light changes and as the threshold is adjusted. The fact that *both* the sensor node and comparator output are essentially stuck at low voltages, and unresponsive to changes in illumination or to the timing/sensitivity potentiometers, indicates a fault localized to the sensing/comparator network rather than to the relay contacts, wiring, or downstream load module.\n\nThe most plausible root cause is an internal failure of the ambient light sensor or the comparator/control IC (or a failed bias/feedback component closely associated with them) that prevents the comparator from changing state and leaves its output in a quasi‑floating, low‑voltage condition, so the relay never receives an active drive signal and the output cables never see 12 V.'
