2026-04-16 12:39:49 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['switched‑cables indicator LED circuit in control (ambient sensor) module'] hypothesis_explanation='The measurements show 12 V present at the control module input (+), but only ~0.36 V at the control output (+), while the negative side is correctly bonded through. Continuity tests with power off report only ~0.10 Ω between input (+) and output (+), which implies that structurally the relay contact and copper trace are intact. Under power, however, the output node collapses to a low voltage, meaning it is being strongly loaded or clamped to near ground via some active or non‑ohmic element inside the control module.\n\nWe have already excluded faults in the relay itself, the comparator/drive circuitry, the ambient light sensor, and its bias network. The remaining element in series/parallel with the switched positive line inside the control module is the ‘switched cables indicator’ LED and its associated resistor or wiring. If this LED circuit has been miswired (e.g. LED placed between output (+) and ground without series resistor, or its leads shorted, or wrong resistor value/placement), it can clamp the output node to a small forward‑bias voltage (~0.3–0.4 V measured at the output), while still allowing a normal continuity reading when unpowered.\n\nThat behavior matches the observed ~0.36 V on the control output (+) regardless of sensor state, while the input (+) remains at ~12 V and the ground path is sound. Therefore the most plausible single‑point cause is a fault or misconnection in the switched‑cables indicator LED circuit within the control (ambient sensor) module, which is effectively shorting or heavily loading the positive output line to near ground under power.'
