2026-04-16 12:40:22 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['polarity / cabling configuration between power supply module and control (ambient sensor) module', 'polarity / cabling configuration between control (ambient sensor) module and load module'] hypothesis_explanation='The electrical measurements are consistent with the control module being powered with correct polarity (its green LED and internal circuits all behave as designed), but with its OUTPUT pair wired so that the nominal ‘+’ line to the load is actually the low‑side (near 0.36 V above ground) of an internal indicator / sensing network rather than the relay‑switched 12 V rail. The negative output is correctly tied to ground.  \n\nBecause the control input pair is reversible at the fast‑connect terminals, and the output pair is similarly reversible, it is possible to have all continuity tests pass and LEDs inside the control module operate, while the lamp receives only ~0.36 V on its positive lead and 0 V on its negative lead. This exactly matches the persistent measurement: ~12 V exists on the control input (+), but the control output (+) remains at ~0.36 V in all light conditions, even though the relay and light‑sensor/comparator sections have been verified and replaced without effect.  \n\nMoreover, reversing the polarity between power and control modules during the diagnostic test produced the same ~0.36 V / ~0 V output behavior, which rules out component‑level failures and points instead to a consistent mis‑assignment of which physical cable is intended to be the switched +12 V. The load module input polarity has been visually confirmed correct relative to the control module labels, so the remaining plausible configuration error is that both the power‑to‑control and control‑to‑load cable pairings are rotated/mismatched with respect to the internal PCB pads of the control module.  \n\nThus the root cause is a configuration/cabling polarity error involving BOTH interfaces of the control module: the ‘+’ and ‘−’ conductors at its input and output are cross‑connected relative to the internal relay‑switched node. Correcting the polarity / wiring at both sides of the control module so that the relay‑switched 12 V node is actually routed to the marked Control Output Cable (+), and that this conductor mates to the Load Input (+), will restore full ~12 V at the lamp and normal operation.'
