2026-04-16 12:41:19 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['main lamp in load module', 'series diode in load module', 'lamp indicator (small bulb) in load module'] hypothesis_explanation='All diagnostics show that the power‑supply module delivers a correct 12 V, that the control (ambient sensor) module is correctly oriented and wired (PSU -> control input, control output -> load), that its relay path and wiring to the output are low‑resistance and behave as designed, and that +12 V is present at the control input while only ~0.36 V appears at the control output when the load is attached. When the control output is measured earlier, it is consistently low, indicating heavy loading on the control output rather than a fault inside the control module itself (which has already been effectively ruled out by component‑level replacement attempts and wiring checks). \n\nThe only remaining plausible location for a fault that can pull the control output down to ~0.36 V while leaving ground at 0 V is in the load module: a shorted or partially shorted component on the positive side before/around the lamp. In this design, the positive line from the control output first enters the load’s series diode and then feeds both the main lamp and the internal lamp indicator in parallel. A short or internal fault in the main lamp, in the series diode, or in the small indicator bulb (for example, diode shorted, lamp filament collapsed causing a near‑short, or indicator lamp/socket fault) would present a very low resistance to ground, clamping the control output to a small voltage despite the relay and wiring being good.\n\nTherefore the root cause is most likely a fault within the load module itself, specifically in the main lamp / series diode / internal lamp‑indicator branch that is loading the control output and preventing normal voltage from appearing at the lamp terminals.'
