2026-04-16 12:41:46 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['timing potentiometer on control (ambient sensor) module', 'associated timing / RC network connection to comparator in control (ambient sensor) module'] hypothesis_explanation='Initially, the lamp exhibited a ~20 s periodic dropout, which is characteristic of a timing or RC network around the comparator/relay rather than a hard failure of the power path. Later diagnostics show that the control module electronics have a solid 12 V supply, the relay and light‑sensor/comparator hardware themselves test good, cabling and polarities between all modules are correct, the load module (diode and both lamps) is good, and there is no mis‑wiring of grounds or outputs. Yet the control output positive line sits at ~0.36 V instead of tracking the 12 V input when the relay should be closed.\n\nThe only remaining internal circuitry that can (a) periodically interrupt drive to the relay and (b) drag the positive path down without being covered by previous repair attempts is the timing potentiometer and its associated timing/RC network connection into the comparator. A faulty or mis‑soldered timing pot (e.g., wiper intermittently open, wrong value, or short to a bias node) or a bad connection from this network to the comparator input can cause the comparator to hover in an indeterminate region, sometimes energizing the relay and sometimes not, leading to the 20‑s on/off cycling originally observed. Subsequent tests, performed after the intermittent behavior stopped reproducibly, would then show a stuck state (output low around 0.36 V) despite otherwise healthy components.\n\nTherefore the root cause is most plausibly a defective or misconnected timing potentiometer / timing RC network in the ambient‑sensor control module.'
