2026-04-16 12:42:14 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['relay contact wiring / PCB connection between relay input and output in control (ambient sensor) module'] hypothesis_explanation='Measurements show 11.99 V on the relay input (from Control Input +) and only ~0.36 V on the relay output node, with the drop occurring directly across the relay contact. Continuity tests from Control Input (+) to Control Output (+) with power off report very low resistance (~0.10 Ω), so the physical contact/coil is not open in the static test. However, under operating voltage the contact behaves as if almost open or miswired, allowing only a tiny leakage voltage (~0.36 V) through. Since the relay device itself and its drive circuitry have already been ruled out as faulty, the remaining plausible cause is an incorrect or defective PCB/wiring connection of the relay contact: for example, the common and normally‑open pins being mis‑routed, a hairline crack or poor solder joint at the relay input or output pad, or a trace mistake causing the relay output node to be fed through an unintended high‑impedance path instead of the intended low‑resistance contact. This would give near‑zero ohms in a low‑current continuity test (through alternate paths) yet drop almost the entire 12 V when the load is applied, yielding the observed ~0.36 V at the output and preventing the lamp from lighting. Repairing the relay contact wiring/PCB connection should restore a solid 12 V path to the Control Output (+) and thus to the load.'
