2026-04-16 12:42:40 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control (ambient sensor) module PCB copper / wiring between measurement test points and actual relay circuit'] hypothesis_explanation='All active components have now been ruled out as faulty: the comparator/sensor, timing network, relay coil, relay contacts, indicator LED circuit, load module (bulbs and diode), and PSU module all test nominal. The relay contact itself directly between its input and output pins measures 0.01 Ω, so it is a good low‑ohmic switch. Yet, when the circuit is powered in the assembled configuration, the node that is *believed* to be the relay output (feeding the indicator LED and Control Output Cable +) sits at only 0.36 V while the relay input is at 11.99 V, implying a large effective series resistance between them during operation.\n\nSince the relay contact is confirmed low‑resistance at its pins, the only way to get 11.99 V on the input pad but 0.36 V on the supposed output node is if our voltage measurements during powered tests were actually taken at points that are not connected as assumed—i.e., there is a PCB layout or wiring error that makes the ‘relay output node’ used for measurements different from the true relay output path that goes to the load and indicator LED. In other words, the copper trace / wiring that should connect the relay output pad to the LED/output connector has been mis‑routed or mis‑named on the PCB, causing our measurement node to be tied through some unintended resistive path (or even to the comparator output), giving the misleading 0.36 V reading.\n\nTherefore the most plausible remaining root cause is a PCB copper / wiring error inside the control module: the relay output pad that was probed during voltage measurements is not actually the pad feeding the LED and output cable, or it is incorrectly tied through other circuitry. Correcting this internal PCB connection (re‑routing/solder‑rework to connect the true relay contact output directly to the indicator LED and Control Output Cable +) should restore a solid ~12 V to the load when the relay is closed and eliminate the abnormal 0.36 V behavior.'
